comment: annin(n)iyami- "cousin", "mother's brother's son"; note: if from Luwoid *anni-nani(ya)-, the meaning is originally 'mother's brother's (offspring)', but it has been generalized at least as far as 'father's sister's son'

annin(n)iyami- "cousin", "mother's brother's son"; note: if from Luwoid *anni-nani(ya)-, the meaning is originally 'mother's brother's (offspring)', but it has been generalized at least as far as 'father's sister's son'

annin(n)iyami- "cousin", "mother's brother's son"; note: if from Luwoid *anni-nani(ya)-, the meaning is originally 'mother's brother's (offspring)', but it has been generalized at least as far as 'father's sister's son'
andaiyant- "son in law". Literally: 'he who has gone in'
LÚkusa- may in some occurrences mean "son in law".
